The Bell-LaPadula no-read-up property (Simple Security Property) states: a subject S can read object O only if the object's classification level is dominated by (less than or equal to) the subject's clearance level. Formally: canRead(S, O) → L(O) ≤ C(S), where L(O) is O's classification and C(S) is S's clearance. The partial order ≤ defines the security lattice hierarchy (e.g., Unclassified ≤ Secret ≤ Top Secret). This prevents information flow from higher-classified (more sensitive) objects to lower-cleared (less privileged) subjects, blocking upward data leakage. The property ensures confidentiality by restricting read access: subjects cannot access information above their authorization level. Violation of this property constitutes an illegal read and represents a security breach of the model's confidentiality guarantee.